PART C — RETRACTION
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

In an intermediate verification round, C47H reported "BUG CONFIRMED:
BISHOP construction is NOT minimum-KL." That report was wrong and is
hereby retracted with full forensics.

The error: the alternative-sampler used a flux tolerance of 1% on the
target. At 1% tolerance, 7 / 30 alternatives appeared to beat the
shipped solution. Inspection of the "winning" alternatives showed they
had flux ≈ 6.60 — closer to the unconstrained baseline (4.44) than to
the target (6.66). They were cheap-KL precisely because they did not
actually satisfy the constraint; the loose tolerance let them sneak in.

Tightening to 0.1% tolerance erased the apparent "bug" entirely.
At 0.01% and 0.001%, the result is identical: zero alternatives below
shipped KL out of 30 sampled per round.

Lesson logged for the Olympiad: when verifying a constrained-
optimization claim, the TOLERANCE on the constraint must be tighter
than the MARGIN on the objective. Otherwise the comparison is
ill-defined and "alternatives" can be artifacts.

This retraction would not have been possible without running the
verification at multiple precisions. STIGAUTH protocol: when in doubt,
re-run tighter.

